\section{Discussion} \label{sec:summary}
The \pkg{digiRhythm} package can make a significant contribution to the animal welfare assessment as it makes the analysis of animal rhythmicity more accessible to researchers. The tool is easy to use, especially it is delivered as an \proglang{R} package. The theoretical details and intuition behind the DFC is explained in section \ref{sec:dfc}. The usage of the package is explained in the section \ref{sec:usage}. Further usage examples can be found in the library's vignettes.

At the date of writing this paper, the current version (v1.1) of the library does not offer the possibility to compute rhythmicity with other techniques such as cosinor analysis (\cite{refinetti2016}). Therefore, there is potential to expand the library's functionality in the future to include other techniques.

Furthermore, it would be interesting to investigate the correlation between the DFC and rhythmicity computed on data from various sources or techniques. In our study, we obtained rhythmicity measures from sensors on animals. It would be valuable to examine the correlation between the rhythmicity of these measures and those obtained from other sources within the same animals, such as blood samples. For instance, \cite{moller2022diurnal} utilized a range of techniques, including set logic, circular cross-correlation, circular clustering, functional enrichment analyses, and least squares regression, on transcriptomic time series data from humans and baboons. Additionally, \cite{plaza2022gps} used GPS data to estimate rhythmicity. Comparing the correlations between rhythmicity measures derived from different types of data and between various techniques could be a useful research area.


Finally, We invite other researchers to contribute to this library by submitting data, code, and techniques that can be shared with the scientific community. By collaborating and sharing these techniques, we can collectively advance our understanding of rhythmicity and its role in various biological systems.

